         <div type="commentary">
            <head>Commentary</head>
            <p>line 1 Cf. the Epaphrodeitus in b, iv, presumably a relation; line 1 ἀρχεφήβου  The term has not been found elsewhere in Cyrenaica, but occurs occasionally in other provinces. 
               In PW V.2, col 2745 it is equated with the official called ἐφήβαρχος, but in IG IV, 589, n. it is suggested that both terms may be used not of a magistrate but of a leading ephebe. This certainly seemd the better sense here, since the man's nickname in line 2 suggests a youth; 
               line 2 Cf. IG XII.2.489 a dead child described as  μελίπνους</p>
         </div>
         
